{"id":"2007.03751","submitter":"Mohamad Latifian","authors":"George Christodoulou, Vasilis Gkatzelis, Mohamad Latifian and Alkmini\n  Sgouritsa","title":"Resource-Aware Protocols for Network Cost-Sharing Games","comments":"Full version of a paper published at Economics and Computation (EC)\n  2020","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1145/3391403.3399528","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the extent to which decentralized cost-sharing protocols can achieve\ngood price of anarchy (PoA) bounds in network cost-sharing games with $n$\nagents. We focus on the model of resource-aware protocols, where the designer\nhas prior access to the network structure and can also increase the total cost\nof an edge(overcharging), and we study classes of games with concave or convex\ncost functions. We first consider concave cost functions and our main result is\na cost-sharing protocol for symmetric games on directed acyclic graphs that\nachieves a PoA of $2+\\varepsilon$ for some arbitrary small positive\n$\\varepsilon$, which improves to $1+\\varepsilon$ for games with at least two\nplayers. We also achieve a PoA of 1 for series-parallel graphs and show that no\nprotocol can achieve a PoA better than $\\Omega(\\sqrt{n})$ for multicast games.\nWe then also consider convex cost functions and prove analogous results for\nseries-parallel networks and multicast games, as well as a lower bound of\n$\\Omega(n)$ for the PoA on directed acyclic graphs without the use of\novercharging.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 7 Jul 2020 19:29:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-09"}
