{"id":"2007.03845","submitter":"Ehud Meir","authors":"Ehud Meir","title":"Universal rings of invariants","comments":"38 pages, 13 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RT math.QA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $K$ be an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero. Algebraic\nstructures of a specific type (e.g. algebras or coalgebras) on a given vector\nspace $W$ over $K$ can be encoded as points in an affine space $U(W)$. This\nspace is equipped with a $\\text{GL}(W)$ action, and two points define\nisomorphic structures if and only if they lie in the same orbit. This leads to\nstudy the ring of invariants $K[U(W)]^{\\text{GL}(W)}$. We describe this ring by\ngenerators and relations. We then construct combinatorially a commutative ring\n$K[X]$ which specializes to all rings of invariants of the form\n$K[U(W)]^{\\text{GL}(W)}$. We show that the commutative ring $K[X]$ has a richer\nstructure of a Hopf algebra with additional coproduct, grading, and an inner\nproduct which makes it into a rational PSH-algebra, generalizing a structure\nintroduced by Zelevinsky. We finish with a detailed study of $K[X]$ in the case\nof an algebraic structure consisting of a single endomorphism, and show how the\nrings of invariants $K[U(W)]^{\\text{GL}(W)}$ can be calculated explicitly from\n$K[X]$ in this case.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Jul 2020 01:51:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-09"}
